name "chap:intro"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the present work is to study the stability of ZND solutions
 of detonation models by an approach that combines ideas from linear stability
 analysis with direct numerical simulations.
 Detonation model usually consist of a system of conservation laws of fluid
 mechanics complemented by the relations connecting hydrodynamics to thermodynam
ics and chemistry.
 Mathematically, such a system admits a ZND solution—solution which is a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

one-dimensional planar wave propagating with a constant velocity.
 However, such solutions are unstable to small perturbations and almost
 never observed in physical experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why is it important to study detonation stability? During detonation, chemical
 energy of an explosive is released after compression of the explosive by
 a shock wave, so that the whole process occurs with significant increase
 of pressure—typically, 20–60 bars for gaseous mixtures.
 Deviation of detonation process from ZND regime can drastically change
 the maximum pressure attained, therefore, it is important to know the stability
 of ZND regime in engineering applications, such as construction of chemical
 factories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Detonation phenomenon gained attention of the researchers at the end of
 nineteenth century after the series of explosions happened in coal mines
 in France.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MallardChatelier1881"

\end_inset

 and independently 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BerthelotVieille1882"

\end_inset

 studied the detonation in glass tubes and found that detonation distinguishes
 from combustion in that the speed of propagation is supersonic with respect
 to the initial gaseous mixture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

long time, it was believed that the detonation propagates as plane wave
 with constant velocity.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chapman1899"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jouguet1905"

\end_inset

 developed first successful theory based on the idea of instantaneous chemical
 reaction occurring inside the detonation front.
 Agreement of the detonation velocity obtained from this theory, with the
 results of the physical experiments of that time, determined the longtime
 success of the Chapman–Jouguet theory (in the following we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

CJ theory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Later, in 1940s, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zeldovich1940"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Neumann1942"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Doering1943"

\end_inset

 independently of each other elaborated on the Chapman–Jouguet theory, and,
 with an assumption of chemical reactions with finite rates, created a theory
 (which is known now as ZND theory, after its creators) of detonation, in
 which detonation wave is represented as a complex consisting of the shock
 wave and following reaction zone, such that the length of the reaction
 zone is constant.
 Shock wave propagates into the initial gas mixture, compresses and ignites
 the gas, so that the gas undergoes chemical transformations in the reaction
 zone.
 The end of the reaction zone moves at the same speed as the detonation
 front, so that the thickness of the reaction zone is constant.
 ZND theory is discussed in detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "CourantFriedrichs1948,ZeldovichKompaneets1960"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, new physical experiments conducted to confirm the ZND theory found
 discrepancy between measurements and the theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "White1961,VoytsekhovskiyEtAl1963"

\end_inset

.
 It turned out that detonation front has a complex three-dimensional structure
 with new transverse shock waves appearing inside the reaction zone.
 So, although ZND theory predicts one-dimensional steady wave solutions
 which are mathematically feasible, these solutions are unstable and generally
 not observable in practice.
\end_layout

