\begin_layout Standard
CJ theory developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Chapman1899"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jouguet1905"

\end_inset

 was the first successful theory describing detonation phenomenon.
 Its success was determined by the good agreement of the theoretical detonation
 velocity and the velocity observed in the physical experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Main properties of this theory are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation occurs in the motionless ambient mixture at uniform thermodynamic
 state with no chemical reactions;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation wave is represented as a shock wave propagating into the mixture
 with constant velocity;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation velocity is very fast, and the main driver of energy transfer
 is convection, so the heat conduction and viscous dissipation are neglected;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation front is represented as a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

jump discontinuity;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
chemical reaction is caused by compression in the detonation front;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
chemical reaction is instantaneous, so that chemical equilibrium is attained
 right behind the shock.
\end_layout

