\begin_layout Standard
The hydrodynamic state right behind the front is defined by Rankine–Hugoniot
 conditions, which express conservation of fluxes of mass, momentum and
 total specific enthalpy across the detonation front:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\backslash
label{eq:intro:cj-znd:cj:conservation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho_{\text{b}}\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right) & =-\rho_{\textrm{\text{\text{b}}}}D,\\
p_{\text{b}}+\rho_{\text{b}}\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right)^{2} & =p_{\text{a}}+\rho_{\text{a}}D^{2},\\
e_{\text{b}}+\frac{p_{\text{b}}}{\rho_{\text{b}}}+\frac{\left(u_{\text{b}}-D\right)^{2}}{2} & =e_{\textrm{b}}+\frac{p_{\textrm{b}}}{\rho_{\textrm{b}}}+\frac{D^{2}}{2},
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 denote density, velocity, pressure, and internal energy, respectively;
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the detonation velocity; subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes quantities in ambient mixture ahead of the detonation wave; subscript
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

b
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes quantities in burned mixture behind the detonation wave.
 The ambient mixture is defined by known quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\text{a}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we have four unknowns (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

) and only three equations (
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\mathrm{b}}$
\end_inset

 is found using thermodynamic relation 
\begin_inset Formula $e=e\left(p,\rho\right)$
\end_inset

), thus, the closure condition is required.
 It appears in this theory as the hypothesis based on the following observation.
 Detonation wave is stable, thus, the burned state is isolated from the
 acoustic waves that can appear behind the wave due to the expansion of
 reaction products.
 Therefore, at the burned state local flow velocity relative to the detonation
 wave must be sonic:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{\mathrm{\text{b}}}-D=-c_{\text{b}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\text{b}}$
\end_inset

 is the sound speed in burned mixture.
 This condition coupled with conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
eqref{eq:intro:cj-znd:cj:conservation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and with an explicit equation of state of the calorically perfect gas
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{\text{b}}=\frac{p}{\left(\gamma-1\right)\rho}-Q,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the ratio of specific heats, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the heat release of the reaction, allows to compute Chapman–Jouguet detonation
 velocity of steady reaction 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\DCJ$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DCJ=\sqrt{c_{\text{a}}^{2}+\frac{\gamma^{2}-1}{2}Q}+\sqrt{\frac{\gamma^{2}-1}{2}Q},
\]

\end_inset

and hence, compute the burned state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
ZND theory
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:intro:cj-znd:znd"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CJ theory was successful in the first decades of 20th century, because of
 the agreement between detonation velocity observed in the physical experiments
 and theoretical minimal possible velocity.
 However, assumption of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

instantaneous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 chemical reaction inside the detonation front was weak under the following
 consideration.
 The thickness of the front is about several mean free paths, so that molecules
 of a gas do not have much possibility to collide.
 At the same time, chemical reactions need many thousands of collisions
 of molecules to change chemical composition significantly, so that chemical
 equilibrium can be attained only on the distances many times longer than
 the front thickness.
 This consideration led researchers to extend the CJ theory, and in 1940s
 independently of each other 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zeldovich1940"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Neumann1942"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Doering1943"

\end_inset

 developed the new theory, now known as the ZND theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Main assumptions of this theory are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation wave propagates into the motionless ambient mixture at uniform
 thermodynamic state with no chemical reactions;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation wave propagates with constant velocity;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation velocity is very fast, and the main driver of energy transfer
 is convection, so the heat conduction and viscous dissipation are neglected;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detonation front is represented as jump discontinuity;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
chemical reaction is caused by compression in the detonation front;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the rate of chemical reaction is finite, such that chemical equilibrium
 is attained at some distance behind the shock;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the whole process is steady in the reference frame attached to the front.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, in ZND theory, detonation wave is considered as a complex consisting
 of a shock wave, which compresses the gas to the state in which chemical
 reaction can occur, and a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

following reaction zone.
 To continue with a concrete example, we, as previously, consider calorically
 perfect gas, in which one irreversible unimolecular reaction 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\text{A}\to\text{B}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurs with the ratio of specific heats of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{B}$
\end_inset

 being the same; the degree of completeness of the reaction is denoted by
 the reaction progress variable
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 in an ambient mixture and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

 in the end of the reaction zone where chemical equilibrium is attained.
 The state right behind the shock (in the point known as von
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Neumann point in the ZND theory) is still unreacted and connected to the
 ambient state by the Rankine–Hugoniot conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{\text{s}}\left(u_{\text{s}}-D\right) & =-\rho_{\text{a}}D,\\
p_{\text{s}}+\rho_{\text{s}}\left(u_{\text{s}}-D\right)^{2} & =p_{\text{a}}+\rho_{\text{a}}D^{2},\\
e_{\textsc{s}}+\frac{p_{\textsc{s}}}{\rho_{\textsc{s}}}+\frac{\left(u_{\textsc{s}}-D\right)^{2}}{2} & =e_{\text{a}}+\frac{p_{\text{a}}}{\rho_{\textsc{\text{a}}}}+\frac{D^{2}}{2},\\
\lambda_{\textsc{s}} & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

s
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes von
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Neumann point, and internal energy 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\mathrm{\text{s}}}$
\end_inset

 does not contain any chemical energy released.
 Rankine–Hugoniot conditions consist of four relations but contain five
 unknown quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{\text{s}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

; therefore, the closure condition is required to find these quantities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flow in the reaction zone is described by steady reactive Euler equations
 written in the reference frame attached to the shock:
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\backslash
label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:steady-euler-ode}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\od{\left(\rho\left(u-D\right)\right)}x & =0,\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:steady-euler-ode-continuity}\\
\od{\left(\rho\left(u-D\right)^{2}+p\right)}x & =0,\\
\od{\left(\rho\left(u-D\right)\left(e+\frac{p}{\rho}+\frac{u^{2}}{2}\right)\right)}x & =0,\\
\od{\left(\rho\left(u-D\right)\lambda\right)}x & =\rho\omega\left(p,\rho,\lambda\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(p,\rho,\lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is the production rate of the product.
 The first three equations can be easily integrated, while the last one
 can be simplified by using product rule for differentiation and continuity
 equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:steady-euler-ode-continuity"

\end_inset

, which yields
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\backslash
label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:euler}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho\left(u-D\right) & = & \mbox{const}_{1},\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-mass}\\
\rho\left(u-D\right)^{2}+p & = & \mbox{const}_{2},\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-momentum}\\
e+\frac{p}{\rho}+\frac{u^{2}}{2} & = & \mbox{const}_{3},\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-energy}\\
\od{\lambda}x & = & \frac{\omega\left(p,\rho,\lambda\right)}{u-D},
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

which can be integrated, and the flow state can be found once we know the
 detonation velocity, as it enters the equations as a parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-mass"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-momentum"

\end_inset

) can be manipulated to get an equation of the Rayleigh–Michel
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
-
\end_layout

\end_inset

son line:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p-p_{\text{a}}=\rho_{\text{a}}^{2}D^{2}\left(v_{\text{a}}-v\right),\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:rayleigh-line}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1/\rho$
\end_inset

 is a specific volume.
 The Rayleigh–Michelson line is straight line with a slope 
\begin_inset Formula $-\rho_{\text{a}}^{2}D^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

–
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 plane and depends on the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-mass"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd-energy"

\end_inset

) can be manipulated to exclude velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and obtain the equation for a
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

family of Hugoniot curves
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e\left(p,v,\lambda\right)-e_{\text{a}}(p,v,0)=\frac{1}{2}\left(p+p_{\text{a}}\right)\left(v_{\text{a}}-v\right),\label{eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:hugoniot-curve}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which depend on parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As both equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:rayleigh-line"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro:cj-znd:znd:hugoniot-curve"

\end_inset

 follow from the same conservation laws, any given Rayleigh–Michelson line
 must intersect with the whole family of Hugoniot curves for every 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\lambda\leq1$
\end_inset

, otherwise the ZND detonation wave is not possible.
 From the whole family of Hugoniot curves the most important one for intersectio
n is the equilibrium Hugoniot curve, namely, the curve corresponding to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
 Looking at the Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:intro:cj-znd:znd:znd-v-p-diagram"

\end_inset

, we can notice that the Rayleigh–Michelson line and equilibrium Hugoniot
 curve has two possibilities to intersect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{\text{CJ}}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the gas state 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 abruptly from point
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to point
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and then continuously changes along the Rayleigh–Michelson line towards
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, where the Rayleigh–Michelson line and the equilibrium Hugoniot curve are
 tangent to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $D>D_{\text{CJ}}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the gas state 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 from point 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to point 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

