\begin_layout Section
Overview of the present work
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:intro:overview"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the present work we develop a novel method for linear stability analysis
 of detonations, namely, the stability of steady travelling-wave solutions
 (to which we refer as ZND solutions in this work) of different detonation
 models varying from the models based on reactive Euler equations with one-
 and two-step reaction mechanisms to the Fickett's detonation analog.
 Here we give an overview of the method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider one-dimensional flow of a gas which is ignited by a detonation
 shock with consequent chemical reaction or reactions.
 Gas is assumed to be inviscid such that the flow is described by a system
 of hyperbolic balance laws:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec z_{t}+\vec f(\vec z)_{x}=\vec s(\vec z),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec z\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a system state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec f\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 the flux function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec s\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 the source term.
 Rankine–Hugoniot conditions connect the state ahead of the shock with the
 postshock state.
 The method is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Switch to the system moving with the detonation wave and write equations
 in a nonconservative form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec z_{t}+\left(\mat A(\vec{z})-D\mat I\right)\vec z{}_{x}=\vec s(\vec z),\label{eq:intro:system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the detonation-wave velocity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mat A}\in\R^{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec f$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mat I\in\R^{n}$
\end_inset

 the identity matrix.
 Now Rankine–Hugoniot conditions become boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the ZND solution for the given model by omitting time dependence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mat A(\vec{\bar{z}})-\bar{D}\mat I\right)\vec{\bar{z}}_{x}=\vec s(\vec{\bar{z}}),\label{eq:intro:eigenvalue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which involves finding speed 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{D}$
\end_inset

, which is an eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro:eigenvalue"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Linearize the system 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:intro:system"

\end_inset

 about the ZND solution.
 Linearize the Rankine–Hu
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
-
\end_layout

\end_inset

go
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
-
\end_layout

\end_inset

niot conditions.
 This results in an linear unsteady system in which unknowns are the perturbatio
ns of the ZND solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec z'_{t}+\mat A(\vec{\bar{z}})z'_{x}+\mat B(\vec{\bar{z}})\vec z'-\od{\vec{\bar{z}}}x\psi'=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prime
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denotes perturbations with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'$
\end_inset

 being the perturbations of detonation velocity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Pose the linear unsteady problem consisting of the linear system along with
 linearized Rankine–Hugoniot conditions as a boundary condition on the upstream
 boundary and outflow boundary condition on the downstream boundary.
 Set initial condition using functions of magnitude much smaller than the
 magnitude of ZND quantities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solve the obtained linear linear unsteady problem numerically recording
 the time series of the perturbation of detonation velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, postprocess the resultant time series to extract the growth rates
 and frequencies (stability spectrum).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is crucial that the last step (postprocessing) is done as efficiently
 as possible.
 In the early stages of this work we planned to achieve this goal using
 nonlinear least-squares method, however, in the case when the time series
 of the perturbation of detonation velocity contain multiple modes growing
 and decaying at different rates, it is become difficult to choose an initial
 guess required by the nonlinear method.
 Further research of the methods applicable for extracting of the growth
 rates and frequencies led us to the Prony's method
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hildebrand1987"

\end_inset

, which is the method (actually predating the Fourier method) for decomposition
 of the time series into the linear combination of complex-valued exponential
 functions.
 However, its application in our work did not yield much success as we were
 not able to extract multiple exponential functions due to numerical instabiliti
es.
\end_layout

